  "prompt": "Is this sentence grammatically correct \"the shirt is not expensive, I bought it cheap\"?",
  "response": "The sentence **\"The shirt is not expensive, I bought it cheap\"** is understandable, but it could be improved for grammatical correctness and clarity. Specifically, it combines two independent clauses with a comma, which is a **comma splice**. To fix this, you can either separate the clauses into two sentences or use a conjunction or semicolon.\n\nHere are some grammatically correct alternatives:\n\n1. **\"The shirt is not expensive; I bought it cheap.\"** (Using a semicolon)\n2. **\"The shirt is not expensive, and I bought it cheap.\"** (Using a conjunction)\n3. **\"The shirt is not expensive. I bought it cheap.\"** (Two separate sentences)\n\nAdditionally, \"cheap\" in this context is informal. A more formal option would be **\"at a low price\"**:\n\n- **\"The shirt is not expensive, so I bought it at a low price.\"**\n\nLet me know if you'd like further help! \ud83d\ude0a",
